  "prompt": "Is it possible to send a man on Halley's Comet?",
  "response": "Sending a human to Halley's Comet would be extremely challenging, if not currently impossible, for several reasons:\n\n1. Distance: Halley's Comet has a highly elliptical orbit that takes it far beyond the orbit of Neptune, with its closest approach to the Sun (perihelion) being between the orbits of Venus and Mercury.\n\n2. Speed: The comet travels at extremely high velocities, making approach and landing difficult.\n\n3. Extreme conditions: The comet experiences dramatic temperature changes and is exposed to intense solar radiation.\n\n4. Limited time window: Halley's Comet only passes near Earth approximately every 75-76 years, with a very brief window of visibility.\n\n5. Technological limitations: Current spacecraft and life support technologies are not advanced enough to support a human mission of such long duration and complexity.\n\nWhile robotic missions like ESA's Giotto spacecraft have successfully studied Halley's Comet during its 1986 pass, a human mission remains beyond our current technological capabilities. Any potential human mission would require significant advancements in propulsion, life support, radiation protection, and long-duration space travel technologies.",
